    "recap_headline": "Xavier University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "CINCINNATI\n- Xavier dropped the second of three games with Evansville, 6-4, on Saturday afternoon at Hayden Field to even the series at 1-1 with the finale set for Sunday.\nThe Musketeers moved to 6-14 on the year, while the Purple Aces improved 4-13.\nAfter two scoreless innings, Evansville got on the board first, scoring three in the top of the third frame, then posting another three-run frame in the fifth to take a 6-0 lead.\nXavier got on the board in the bottom of the fifth, with\nDonavan Canterberry\nleading off the inning with a single, moving to second on an error and coming home on a double from\nClay Burdette\n.\nLandon Mensik\nled off the sixth with a walk and moved to second on a single from\nPeter Johnson\nand third on a walk from\nJason Jelic\n. Canterberry took a bases-loaded walk to bring in Mensik, cutting Evansville's lead to 6-2.\nJorge Valdes\nfollowed Canterberry's walk with a ground ball to bring in Johnson to make it 6-3.\nXavier made it four unanswered runs in the seventh with\nTommy Townsend\nleading off with a single, moving to second after\nTanner Thomas\nwas hit by a pitch and third on a ground out from Johnson. A sac fly from\nLuke Hammond\nbrought Townsend in to cut the Purple Aces' advantage to 6-4 but the Musketeers were unable to get any closer, falling by the two-run margin.\nXavier wraps up the series with the Purple Aces on Sunday afternoon, with first pitch set for 1 p.m. from Hayden Field on ESPN+.\nAT THE PLATE\nClay Burdette\nwent 3-4 with a walk, driving in an RBI with a double.\nLuke Hammond\nfinished with a hit (1-3) and picked up an RBI on a sac fly.\nDonavan Canterberry\nfinished 1-3 with a walk, driving in an RBI and scoring arun.\nJorge Valdes\ndrove in an RBI with a ground ball.\nPeter Johnson\nwent 2-5 with a run scored.\nTommy Townsend\nfinished 2-5 at the plate\u00a0and scored a run.\nLandon Mensik\ngot aboard with a walk, scoring a run.\nJosh Stonehouse\nfinished with a hit (1-5) as the Musketeers out-hit the Purple Aces, 10-7, for the day.\nJason Jelic\nrecorded a walk, one of four on the day for the Musketeers.\non the mound\nJack Nobe\nmade the start, going 5.0 innings, allowing six runs, four earned, on six hits and four walks, striking out six.\nJack DeTienne\nentered for the sixth, going a career-long 4.0 innings without allowing a run and giving up just one hit and one walk while striking out a pair.\nHIGHLIGHTS"
